Trigger in Azure pipelines:

Single branch trigger (main) → Runs pipeline only when code is pushed to one specific branch (main).
Multi-branch trigger → Runs pipeline for multiple branches like main, dev, release.
Wildcard branch trigger (feature/*) → Runs pipeline for dynamically matching branch patterns.
Include / Exclude branch trigger → Runs or skips pipeline based on specific branch filters.
Path-based trigger → Runs pipeline only when specific files or folders are changed.
Branch + Path combined trigger → Runs pipeline only if both branch and file conditions match.
Pull Request (PR) trigger → Runs pipeline when a PR is created or updated.
Tag-based trigger → Runs pipeline when a Git tag (e.g., v1.0) is created.
Scheduled trigger (cron) → Runs pipeline automatically at defined time intervals.
Manual trigger (trigger: none) → Pipeline runs only when manually triggered.
Batch trigger → Combines multiple commits into a single pipeline run.
Pipeline trigger (pipeline dependency) → Triggers one pipeline after another pipeline completes.
Build completion trigger → Starts pipeline when another build finishes successfully.
Resource trigger (repo/container/pipeline) → Runs pipeline based on changes in external resources.
Environment-based trigger (with approvals/conditions) → Controls deployment based on approvals and environment rules.

