✅ 1. What is strategy
👉 strategy = defines how a job runs\

Types:
- runOnce     -- Runs job only once & Used in deployments
- rolling     -- deploy in batches &  Used in production rollout (safe deployment)
- Canary      -- Gradual deployment & Used for partial rollout

Controls execution behavior
Used in:
normal jobs ✅
deployment jobs ✅


✅ 2. Types of strategy
✅ 1. runOnce (most common)
👉 Runs job only once
YAML
strategy:  
runOnce:    
  deploy:      
    steps:        
      - script: echo "Run once"Show more lines

✔ Used in deployments

✅ 2. rolling (for deployment)
👉 Deploy in batches

strategy:  rolling:    maxParallel: 2

✔ Used in production rollout (safe deployment)

✅ 3. canary
👉 Gradual deployment
strategy:  
  canary:    
    increments: [10, 20]

✔ Used for partial rollout

✅ 3. What is matrix
👉 matrix = run same job multiple times with different values

Runs jobs in parallel
Useful for:

testing multiple OS
multiple versions
multiple environments




✅ 4. Basic Matrix Example
YAML
trigger: 
- none
pool:  
  vmImage: 'ubuntu-latest'
jobs:
- job: Build  
  strategy:    
    matrix:      
    node14:  
    NODE_VERSION: '14'      
    node16:        
    NODE_VERSION: '16'  
    steps:    
    - script: echo "Node version $(NODE_VERSION)"

✅ Output

Job runs 2 times:

NODE_VERSION=14 ✅
NODE_VERSION=16 ✅




✅ 5. Matrix with multiple values


✅ 6. Key difference (very important)

strategy → defines execution method
matrix → defines multiple job variations


✅ 7. Real-world use

Test app on:

Java 8 / Java 11 ✅
Node 14 / 16 ✅
Ubuntu / Windows ✅

✅ 8. One-line summary

strategy → how job runs
matrix → how many variations of job run


✅ 9. Interview quick example
👉 “Using matrix strategy, we run the same build job across multiple runtime versions in parallel to ensure compatibility.”

