✅ 1. What is Deployment Group
👉 Deployment Group = a collection of target servers (VMs) where application will be deployed

Used for classic release pipelines
Helps deploy app to multiple machines at once


✅ 2. One-line definition
👉 “Deployment group is a logical group of machines used to run deployment jobs from Azure DevOps pipelines.”

✅ 3. Purpose

✅ Deploy application to multiple servers
✅ Manage on-prem or VM-based deployments
✅ Centralized deployment control


✅ 4. How it works

Create deployment group in Azure DevOps
Install agent (deployment agent) on each server
Add servers to deployment group
Pipeline targets the group
Deployment runs on all servers


✅ 5. Architecture (simple flow)
Azure DevOps Pipeline
        ↓
Deployment Group
        ↓
Multiple Servers (VM1, VM2, VM3)
        ↓
App deployed on all


✅ 6. Example (concept)
👉 You have 3 production servers

prod-server-1
prod-server-2
prod-server-3

➡ Add all to deployment group prod-group
➡ Pipeline deploys to all 3 machines ✅

✅ 7. Where used

On-prem servers ✅
Virtual Machines ✅
Legacy applications ✅


✅ 8. Deployment Group vs Environment (IMPORTANT)


Deployment Group

Used in classic pipelines
VM-based deployment
Older approach



Environment (recommended)

Used in YAML pipelines
Supports approvals, checks
Modern approach ✅




✅ 9. Key components

Deployment group ✅
Deployment agent ✅
Target machines ✅


✅ 10. Real-world example
👉 Banking application deployment:

App built → artifact created ✅
Deployment group targets 10 servers ✅
Deployment job runs on all servers ✅


✅ 11. Key interview points

Group of target machines
Requires agent installation on each VM
Used mainly in classic release pipelines
Replaced by environments in YAML pipelines

